caption: Exquisite Eglise with spectacular dome and interior in the ceilings! Must visit when you are strolling around the 3rd arrondissement of Paris city. And it’s located just at the same building with the Musée des Arts et Metiers. The ivory narrow hallway with the classical style of decoration makes you feel like you are thrown into the medieval century. If you like daydreaming like me, this Eglise is quite recommended.

This former monastery church has now been magnificently restored and is part of the Art et Metiers Museum located on the metro of the same name. Today it houses the Foucault pendulum in the choir and the first flying machines, steam trains, cars in the nave - in short, the transportation of the past: well worth seeing for the whole family!

The idea of ​​converting an old Catholic church into a huge hall with an exhibition of physics achievements even looks like a bit of a mockery But the result was impressive - especially the models of the first airplanes under the roof. LIBERTY STATUE (interior) Liberty Enlightening the World, better known as the Statue of Liberty, is one of the most famous monuments in the United States. It was offered by France, as a sign of friendship between the two nations, to celebrate the centenary of the American Declaration of Independence. The statue was inaugurated on October 28, 1886, while in 1879, Frédéric-Auguste Bartholdi called on the engineer Gustave Eiffel for the internal structure of the statue. The Museum of Arts and Crafts allows you to discover the history of this statue and the stages of its construction. Statue of Liberty: a plaster and a bronze at the Museum of Arts and Crafts: It is not in bronze but it weighs its weight. Made entirely of plaster, the construction model which rests in the Museum of Arts and Crafts weighs no less than 14 tonnes. It is this that Auguste Bartholdi will use to create, by enlargement, the New York Statue of Liberty. The museum also houses a reproduction, also in plaster, scale 1/16, from 1876. This model was also used to make the bronze statue which has stood, since 2010, outside the museum.

Demonstration of Foucaud's pendulum, very interesting. Don't think you know everything about the Earth's rotation until you see this demonstration. The guide is very friendly and her explanations are very clear and really fascinating.

The Saint-Martin des Champs church located in the Arts et Métiers buildings is today part of the Arts et Métiers museum. The Saint-Martin des Champs Catholic church is located rue Albert Thomas, next to Place de la République.

The miracle of curing a leper, performed by Saint Martin of Tours on his way to the north of the city in 385, led to the construction of the church of Saint-Martin-des-Champs, on the right bank (3rd), much further to the south. north than most houses in the city.
